BHP Billiton, BP, Diageo, Game Group: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t
-- 
2011-04-11T06:52:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-10/diageo-lloyds-rolls-royce-u-k-irish-equity-market-preview.html
The following is a list of
companies that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and
Irish markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are
from the last market close.  Futures contracts on the benchmark  FTSE 100 Index (UKX)  climbed
0.2 percent to 6,010 at 7:52 a.m. in London. The FTSE 100 rose
48.38, or 0.8 percent, to 6,055.75 on April 8, while the  FTSE
All-Share Index (ASX)  gained 0.8 percent and Ireland’s ISEQ Index
advanced less than 0.1 percent.  3i Group Plc (III)  : The U.K. private-equity investor
hired Blackstone Group LP restructuring staff to work with
Enterprise Plc, a U.K. company that lays pipes for utilities,
the Sunday Telegraph reported, citing unidentified people close
to the matter. The shares retreated 0.1 percent to 275.1 pence.  888 Holdings Plc (888)  (888 LN): The U.K.-listed Internet
gambling company that may be bought by Ladbrokes Plc said Chief
Executive Officer Gigi Levy will step down “to pursue other
interests.” The stock was unchanged at 46 pence.  Allied Irish Banks Plc (ALBK)  : The Dublin-based,
government-controlled lender may shed almost 2,000 jobs, the
Sunday Times said, without citing anyone. The bank will scale
down its loan portfolio by as much as 19 billion euros ($27.5
billion) even as it keeps First Trust Bank, the bank’s unit in
 Northern Ireland , the newspaper said. The stock slumped 6.4
percent to 28 euro euros.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP)  : The world’s largest mining
company denied that it plans to buy  Royal Dutch Shell Plc (RDSA) ’s
stake in Woodside Petroleum Ltd. in a A$46 billion ($48.6
billion) takeover.  BHP “is not aware of any basis for the market
speculation” for media reports linking it to Woodside, the
company said in a statement. The Sunday Times reported yesterday
that BHP has held talks with Shell.  BHP’s shares climbed 2.7 percent to 2,585.5 pence.  BP Plc (BP/)  : The oil producer’s board may replace
former Chief Executive Officer  Tony Hayward  as a director of its
50 percent-owned Moscow-based affiliate TNK-BP, the Sunday
Telegraph reported without saying where it got the information.
A spokesman for BP denied last night that Hayward will be
replaced as a non-executive director at TNK-BP, according to the
Sunday Telegraph.  The shares rose 0.8 percent to 478.5 pence.  Diageo Plc (DGE)  : The owner of Smirnoff vodka, which
agreed to buy Turkish spirits producer Mey Icki for about $2.1
billion in February, received a pledge from the Turkish
government that it will take a “balanced” approach to the
alcoholic drinks industry, Hurriyet newspaper said citing Andrew Morgan, Diageo’s president of European operations. The shares
increased 0.4 percent to 1,201 pence.  Game Group Plc (GMG)  : The U.K. electronic games retailer
plans to name former Ladbrokes Plc Chief Executive Officer Chris
Bell as chairman, the Sunday Times reported, without saying
where it got the information. The stock gained 1.4 percent to
54.5 pence.  GKN Plc (GKN)  : GKN said first-quarter sales rose to 1.49
billion pounds from 1.31 billion pounds for the year-earlier
period. The shares climbed 1.3 percent to 202.4 pence.  GlaxoSmithKline Plc (GSK)  : The U.K.’s biggest drugmaker
plans to invest 500 million Egyptian pounds ($83.8 million) in
the north African country over the next five years, it said. The
stock advanced 0.3 percent to 1,220 pence.  HMV Plc (HMV LN): The U.K. retailer of books, music and
DVDs, postponed a rights offer because of shareholder hostility
to the plan, the Observer reported, citing advisers to the
company and unidentified investors. The stock retreated 2.2
percent to 11.3 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Blanche Gatt in  London  at 
 bgatt@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
